Food to blame European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, prices were higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate; in its discretion, the reduction of interest rates would favor the rise in commodity prices and the slight decrease in unemployment to create an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a mess: one has to “counter” inflation in order to rule out the need for later action.
In November, the inflation rate reached a record twelve-year high in Germany at 3.3 percent; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the Eurozone is driven by rising food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat listings rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant price increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose 52 percent this year – last month the price per barrel of black gold reached $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next three to four months, analysts expect an inflation rate of 3 percent, but the average annual rate is 2.1 percent.
Experts predict that the ECB will cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup faces government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz supporters has increased significantly until early December.For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while the support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among the party-loyal voters, the difference is evident thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) of the support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, the MDF and the SZDSZ are under the parliamentary entry barrier: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of voters in both camps increased by one percent.
Compared to the last low, the overall economic mood has deteriorated further – never before has the proportion of those who assess the country’s economic situation as “expressively bad” been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider them “pretty bad.”
After more hopeful outlook in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only one-tenth expect an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents — a historic high — rated the prime minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents generally have a high level of confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the proportion of supporters of Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Approximately 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% who do not trust the leader of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who think that one could manage the dissatisfaction with the prime minister even without a change of government.
After the riots in October last year, 35% still voted for the remainder of the government and the head of government, today this percentage is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent answered that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20 percent would "likely" vote.
For comparison, if the parliamentary elections were held this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty", another 15% consider their participation "likely".
74% would vote against the tuition fee, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily fee.
Based on the group of people "with certainty" who participated in the referendum, the proportions of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84 and 89 percent, respectively.
