In many places, disinfectants are saved.
Last year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overcrowding of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the curbing of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János Hospital, a MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
There was a similar infection at the beginning of the year.
The injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but a short time later the man had to return with an MRSA infection.
As of December 10, this year, 1094 infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens from hospitals were to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as angina, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the funds are overdosed or used incorrectly, the well-responsive bacteria form antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in the elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical head of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the daily life of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned – MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff wears rubber gloves and masks at the care, and we have the necessary antibiotics for treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are taken to the hospital, an infection can not always be avoided.
Testing too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant agent, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is prevalent in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the hospitalized patients and immediately isolate those infected with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not so frequently practiced in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health fund for this examination.
Most cases therefore come to light only when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical head of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the agent, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among ambulatory or primary care patients, microbiological sampling is even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by dropless infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often crowded, the beds are roughly aligned, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the financially less well-positioned hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are fighted everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its mitigation, was included in the government program.
At first signs, the program is successful - as published data shows, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as prevention of infections in hospitals.
