EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements for a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a €300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects with grants from the Cohesion Fund.
The €150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be used for the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has allocated a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contractual partners have signed an agreement of €50 million, which will flow mainly into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
The subway line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of subway financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has funded a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth a total of EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest rates are EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a delay of 8 years, commission free.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is looking attentively at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys in the still cheapest market in the EU, which is becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after place for real estate purchases in the Eastern European area, with affordable ski apartments and seaside houses.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, along the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the runners, however, real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates of Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria wid also attract domestic investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the highly favorable area of Russian recorded more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its best path to becoming one of the most attractive European golf havens, thereby attracting tourists in the other two seasons in addition to the summer and winter season.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in large-scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also aim to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or shattered houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are well-written, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for buyers.
