In the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been an annual price increase of 21 percent.
The price increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are consulting on the Bali Roadmap, which sets out emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between industrialized and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signaled that it is not willing to negotiate concrete figures, but is willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether developed countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on supporting developing countries.
The Adjustment Fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, likely through the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as will be read in the "Piac és Profit".
6 percent of Hungary
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports, on behalf of Hungary, the EU’s efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured at 1990 values), regardless of whether or not the "Agreement after 2012" is successful.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, while the EU with its then 15 member states had already committed to a reduction of 8 percent.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 – a requirement that the country will quite fulfill, as read in the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali – after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would not enter into force after 2012. In this case, a new international emission reduction system would not follow the reduction goal set out in the Kyoto Protocol, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international, Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee of the UN in its recent report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and an increase in global average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Advertising on YouTube
Units of the British army have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban to the network since March 2006.
The footage, filmed with miniature cameras attached to helmets, will be checked at the air force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where it will be posted on the Internet.
Political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under the Defence Headquarters in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Office and the International Peace Forces stationed in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign missions.
This kind of public propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television advertising, according to defence expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the legitimacy of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise with Games
But the army must also fight against amateur footage, which it also puts on the net in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are mostly talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
From the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos shot in operation have already been uploaded to the platform, but this "genre" has only recently been discovered by the British for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free-to-download shooter "America's Army", in which the player can slide into the skin of the soldier as part of a more or less vivid simulation.
