More and more people mobilize for massive strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions will form their coordination committee on Friday for an indefinite strike starting on Monday.
A large protest assembly will be held on Saturday, and on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the work deployment begins.
Strike-related, significant traffic barriers are expected as railway traffic is almost completely shut down, and also the Budapest public transport operators (BKV) strike until 13 a.m.
Details of the strike will be announced on Friday afternoon by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be established, which will be responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A major protest assembly will be held on Saturday, and from Monday on, all organizations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that began on the day of parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss further action.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even possible that there will be a vote on the Health Insurance Act only late in the evening, or even only at midnight.
As a result of the strikes starting on Monday, there will be significant traffic barriers: railway workers stop work indefinitely, the majority of public transport and more than half of Volán companies stop in the morning.
At the same time, there will be motorway blockages in many places.
The call to strike has been followed by numerous unions and civil society organizations - the list of participants is updated on the League website.
Some organizations have announced unlimited strikes, while others are planning a temporary cessation of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement was reached between the Hungarian Railway MÁV and the Free Railway Trade Union VDSZSZ on sufficient services, despite the fact that more and more people are traveling by rail during Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, the BKV will run from start to 13 a.m., at Budapest Airport from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m., the LIGA trade unions for electricity and heat will suspend work for four hours, and the Teachers’ Union and the Democratic Teachers’ Union have called for a 2- or 2-8 hour strike.
The Hungarian Medical Association strikes nationwide alternately at various times, while the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraws the draft reform of health insurance and presents a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
The third requirement is that eligible occupational groups have access to the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer for the secondary lines submitted by the Ministry of Transport and is now demanding a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to Political Capital’s Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, established in August with the support of the “Movement for a Better Hungary”, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute’s “Risk Warning Report” states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the “exacerbating of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term”.
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is likely aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As, this is viewed as a failure by the political leaders: “Personages of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary contrast.”
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremes, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, "significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
Since the fall of 2006, the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been continuously on the rise, so that since the summer of 2007 several organizations have been founded, calling themselves "national self-defense associations".
“It is common to these groups that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while they openly boast of preparing their members for – sometimes armed – defence tasks (disaster protection, national defence, order maintenance), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself,” it said.
All this should be done in accordance with the method which seeks to disguise as a civil initiative various political aspirations based on the political and party disorientation of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association is therefore not only meant to circumvent legal obstacles that could arise in the course of registration in court – it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also pose a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighboring countries as a potential source of danger, so some ultranationalist politicians of certain neighboring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as a confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the whole region has grown.
As, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard were the mass Roma riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents as an occasion for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organization is “national protection.”
In her opinion, in the past 17 years, a real “Gypsy terror” was felt in Bulgaria, but the state remained inactive and indifferent.
And further: the initiative would have sparked a fierce debate in the Bulgarian public.
As I said, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is also demonstrated by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced to set up their own guard for resistance purposes.
As the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that Hungarian Roma will also respond to the threats by organising their own protection, according to the risk warning report of Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, Research Director at Political Capital said at the request of the news office: Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
Risk analysis reports would be published annually, and should risk-changing trends be detectable, the public opinion would be informed, as in the case by issuing the risk warning report.
