In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so the practice of changing working days around holidays has now established itself, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
In the United States and in the United States, the term holiday is also used in a different way.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and public holidays.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are related to major historical events.
We also celebrate New Year, for example: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are working-free days - the latter alone allows the New Year's Eve celebrants to rest.
We have a total of 14 holidays throughout the year.
The national holidays are March 15, commemorating the revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May we celebrate the work, and on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each to Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “workday postponement” has proven in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of prolonged weekends, however, is that we have to work very comfortably on Saturdays before it, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finally completed, has been determined by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employers, public servants and officials of the public service.
Exceptions are only companies and institutions in which the operation continues without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays.
Currently, the working order is only a bit confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life here is still formally standing, as most people take time balancing for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the holiday specially abolished for it.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer shifts on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "set on the head" around the working day so that people can stay at home for just four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so Friday, May 2 may be a rest day.
The second disposal is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, you will have to work ahead of Friday, 24 October.
The end of the year, however, will be completely in the sign of holidays, after starting on December 24, everything remains still, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
