Banks want to deal with the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the U.S. Federal Reserve will be auctioning $40 billion, with another $24 billion for the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 9/11 that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to defending or mitigating the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This move is aimed at eliminating the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing shortage of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group in a report to his clients.
"The coordinated action of central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the U.S. from 65% to about 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unsuccessful loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts expect additional billions of dollars.
"The central banks must have really been afraid of what could happen when they decided to take this approach," said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficulty accessing bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession, potentially affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used for lending money between banks.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, despite the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom having lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as further lowering interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this move by central banks contributes to the warming up of the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the fall of the U.S. real estate market.
