Cuba – the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters serving pizza, ice cream and enchanting cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, Golf and Roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you can find this in abundance.
But there is only one island you can find a lot more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a warehouse or transit warehouse of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the late 20th century.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the Prohibition) was liked and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner and Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, across the wide boulevards, cars that were among the cult symbols of the 1950s of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today ?
On the walls of the Bodeguita in Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails for you as you wish.
And the cult cars of the 1950s drive around Havana to this day, because the once imported shigulis and fiats have long since broken apart in the salty and humid air.
Even though Havana, especially its oldest part, has been severely degraded, nowhere in the vicinity you can find as many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are being cleaned up, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings urgently needed money, there was a green light for this development.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba also offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar pipe from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Exit targets
The most important places are not missed by most visitors to Cuba.
There is no need to write about Varadero or Havana.
It remains only to be mentioned that in the already mentioned property of Hemingway there is a museum, whose visit should not be missed by those who like this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which also weathered rocky areas are covered with dense growth.
This valley is where the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can encounter it when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Her fame and wealth came from slave trade and sugar.
Wealth was embodied in the ornate beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed in the last four hundred years.
Located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, Trinidad is such a remote place that there was no road to connect the area with the rest of the country until the 1950s.
This isolation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was happy that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon to visit Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the “Valley of the Sugar Factories”.
In the evening, you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is described by some as the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly this view will also be influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading there from Guantánamo must cross high and crumbling mountains and run through a landscape hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern suburb of Cuba was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List thanks to its unspoiled nature.
There the best chocolate is made, the church shows the Cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, several table mountains can be seen, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But, as they say, it is better to see with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans say.
Too few troops and the lack of necessary equipment, according to the United States, affect the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Secretary Robert Gates, NATO should draft a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going according to their expectations, this was agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland, by the representatives of the countries that have units stationed in the south of the country.
In addition to the growing resistance from the Taliban, the eight participating countries are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its defence secretary Robert Gates, is urging NATO units to be more active, Britain considers the priority to strengthen the Afghan government’s authority and to intensify development aid.
“In Afghanistan, progress is noticeable, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to enable residents to start developing their own economy and security," Defense Secretary Des Brown told the BBC.
90 percent
The activity of Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the US military.
The number of violent acts has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops stationed in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have come to an absolute limit in terms of the organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
"We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next time and how we can them," Gates said.
This was stated by NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the troops and equipment we need, and that’s too little,” De Hoop told Reuters at the end of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
In recent months, there has also been controversy among the countries involved as to whether all allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
For passivity, Germany was criticized.
