Government debt will rise to 1 trillion in 2009
Each Czech has a government debt of 84,000 Krona.
The total debt rose to SEK 842.7 billion by the end of September.
The government had planned to owe 159.2 billion cousins this year.
However, in early December, the ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
The public debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
In the first nine months of this year, they increased by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance confirmed its debt data for the beginning of October.
Each Czech has a debt of 84,000 Krona.
Over the past year, the state owed more than 111 billion crowns.
"So far, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for the coming year, we may not exceed the one trillion crown limit until 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns,” said David Marek, an analyst at Patria Finance, to iHNed.cz.
Similarly, Vladimír Pikora, analyst at Next Finance, says: “We could reach a trillion over the course of 2009.
When exactly, depends on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it turns out that the situation on the political stage is changing, and politicians should be willing to save more, it could take until 2010.
But I do not assume such a change,” he noted.
Debt is growing
State debt comes from government debt and comes mainly from the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
Government debt is financed by treasury orders, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, by bonds of the European Investment Bank.
This year, the national debt has risen to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state’s foreign debt has increased by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable government debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and fell by 13.7 billion since June.
The average debt maturity has risen to 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased by 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is going.
It is interesting that the growth is most notable in bonds, where the increase is 20 percent.
It’s bad that the debt is rising, but on the other hand it shows that something can be done even before the pension reform comes,” Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
According to the 2007 funding and debt management strategy, the government had planned to raise SEK 159.2 billion for this year.
At the beginning of December, however, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns, thanks to the better development of the state budget policy.
This amount is mainly due to the state budget deficit, which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
These include a maximum of 13.3 billion SEK for the consolidation agency, a 10-billion SEK reserve for pensions, 43 billion SEK for government bond financing and 1.8 billion SEK for bonds at the European Investment Bank.
