At the last meeting in Vienna on Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo concluded a sixth and final discussion session in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversies over the future status of the separatist province.
“It is regrettable that the parties could not come to an agreement on the status,” European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a news conference in Vienna.
Underlining that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart, Frank Wilsner, called on Belgrade and Pristina to meet their commitments to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
"There are no violent acts expected in the near future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time," he added, indicating that there are clear tensions.
End of negotiations on December 10
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the United States and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, represented the sixth and last negotiating session since the troika received an order from the UN last August for a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the recognition of Kosovo’s independence by the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
“Russia has been and remains an advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution,” said Botsane-Kharchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence.
After Kosovo was administered by the UN for eight years, Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to announce it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favor.
Belgrade calls for greater autonomy
“Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached,” the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where these “last chance negotiations” have been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
However, he added that the plan for autonomy proposed by Belgrade “belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.”
The domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, on his part, believed that a compromise should always be sought, and warned the Albanian majority in Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade says it is concerned about a “domino effect” in a region that has been weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible," he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision would be made solely and solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word.
"Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they started: in the Security Council.
Fatmir Sejdiu replied to journalists that “the parliament of Kosovo will have the last word regarding the status” and added that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population will be “coordinated” with the Western countries.
