Spectacular repairs at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the International Space Station (ISS) crew will have spent more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a faulty solar collector, which is essential for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has set several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools "built" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday when the astronauts loaded the Harmony module from the Discovery spacecraft, a large cylinder-shaped part that is expected to soon accommodate European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module labs.
You must be able to supply them with electricity.
So the second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5-ton module for power generation via solar panels already on the ISS to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew went on to restructure the solar collectors of the module, whose span length is 76 meters.
And then it happened that one of the collectors, which can stand out like accordions, was damaged by a stuck cable about a meter long.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to further damage the collector.
The astronauts, who originally left the Discovery spacecraft for a check-through and then were to repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around the end of the 30 meter long remote-controlled arm of the spacecraft to which the station had been attached to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skilled, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
So the 46-year-old learned doctor was chosen to “operate” the “injured” solar collector.
Having carefully examined the damage, he broke through the faulty cable and attached a kind of rail to the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second “Spacewalker” who stayed near the loop, and, from the inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, the crew’s commander.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey shooter wrapped in insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar collectors that generate several hundred volts, the astronauts on board the station had conceived and “bustled.”
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully folded before counting out his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts half a day of relaxation before seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery today, expected to return to Earth on Wednesday.
