A heavy memory
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, stored on a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have so far been unable to be accessed unless with a “humanitarian” intention, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven countries in charge of its administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable investigations, “especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health status of the forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, opposed making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The concentration camps inmates lists or the Gestapo arrest warrants had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with proof of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
“You can expect nothing fundamentally new in these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
