Congress approves the MIFID directive, which came into force on 1 November.
In parallel to the parliamentary preparation, which today concluded its session with the Senate resolution on the amendments to the draft, the government published the provisions arising from the new law with the intention of enabling the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
Representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of congressmen and senators who, in their negotiations and votes, had pursued the goal of establishing the best possible regulation that guarantees the security of investors and regulates individual entrepreneurial activities, thereby guaranteeing a general efficiency of the market.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, the MIFID, which redefines the Regulation on Investment Services, aims to improve investor protection, increase the scrutiny of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive will enable financial advice to specialised firms as well as to natural or legal persons and will also contribute to the establishment of new financial services firms (ESIS), the consulting firms that merge with investment and securities brokerage firms.
Furthermore, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, adding to the regulated circulating markets the multilateral systems for the trading of securities and the systems for the internationalization of trading orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic operators.
The law obliges investment firms to disclose the priorities of their business profile, the confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks in the market and to register all operations carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control task.
The Congressional Economic Commission subsequently envisaged further changes, with the decision that titled bonds now have to be considered “complex” financial assets because of their high risk level for the investor confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis.
Furthermore, the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the fields of work of graduated economists was taken advantage of, 30 years after 1977, when the regulation, which limited the fields of work reserved for economists, was adopted.
The Senate, in turn, established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the economic intermediary working on foreign account, which does not require authorization from the CNMV and can offer its services for the commercialization of products and for the acquisition of customers simultaneously to several investment companies.
