New concerns over gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is swelling between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be impaired.
The majority of Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow takes place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more because the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the main gas transit states in talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine.”
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices drastically up.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s gas supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS “must control foreign workers”
The Scottish State Health Service needs to improve criminal record checks for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation from Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in connection with the June Glasgow airport attack.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish state health service has no precise insight into the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks on a sample of five health authorities were carried out correctly.
The Chief Financial Controller investigated staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a ground car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will conduct checks prior to hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The report of the Chief Auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the Board should take guidance from the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Al we found evidence of these checks in some staff records, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their survey guidelines before hiring highly, but added: “Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information about the number of foreign healthcare workers is available.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in advance of hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
“The report says that NHS Scotland’s current performance tests are working well and it’s not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver,” he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards would have trouble identifying those employees who are on indefinite leave.
The investigation also found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were mostly complied with.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines on pre-employment checks for foreign staff at the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern for me to do this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines on control surveys prior to hiring by all employees – including those from abroad – which is scheduled to be published next month.
