Climate on Venus Could Give a View on Earth's Future
Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit shows that the planet is even more like a twin of the Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But due to the unstoppable carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere due to sunlight and a slower rotation rate, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings from the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which has studied the plants for a year, offer a disturbing glimpse of how the Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said: “It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of Earth, while the planets are otherwise pretty similar.”
“Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus started like Earth billions of years ago, possibly with a habitable environment.”
