The pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not slippery.
No nobility titles appear to have been sold, no Parisian hotel bills paid to any politician, no out-of-marriage toes licked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has covered up donations to the British ruling Labour Party of more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the names of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which the competing Gordon Brown would have done well.
When, two months ago, the prime minister withdrew from demanding an election, stupidly insulting the intelligence of the British by claiming that polls would not have influenced that decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly sharp-minded leader of the Liberal Democrats, expressed, the once feared Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The ruthless rescue of Northern Rock, a beaten bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought out proposals to change tax laws have brought corporate associations against the government.
The tax administration’s loss of personal data of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative plunder.
A trio of retired generals launched an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: being minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the diverse donations of David Abraham; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary general (and its former execution chief) has already resigned.
Nothing of this means that Brown irrevocably breaks down towards resignation.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they find it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he doesn’t even need to be there for a long time, this postponement is over: the public service begins to get dull; the cabinet ministers start chatting; the press is looking for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and pointless.
In a way, Brown’s position is difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he can’t claim to be a new beast.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are linked together with decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s misfortunes — like in the long “money for nobility” investigation into political party financing — voters might assume he was.
However, Brown’s situation is not as bad as it seems.
The misconduct is not as terrible as the conservatives describe it.
Like Mr. Bean, no one has died, or has been completely shattered.
And the remedy, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The new gathering of political donations is a good example.
The garboesque of Abraham, who compares his gifts to his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
It may be, but the decision was not for him.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who rule the country.
Watt, who says he knew of Abraham’s deal, but not that it was illegal, will of course have to ask a few questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s chief fundraiser, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half of the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered that determination by gripping to a well-known instrument, an investigative committee on the subject - led to make the measure full, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "learnings to be drawn from" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr. Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent committee on standards in public life, which has been unoccupied for six months, and moving forward with a comprehensive reform of political party financing.
This would require Labour’s hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly give up their special financial relationship with the unions – bitter pills for a party mate like Mr. Brown.
But he should be aware of some party facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can a victory is through undeniable righteousness and solid competence.
