Goldman Sachs analysts estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spread to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both the outbound rates and the mortgage rates, which measure the percentage of loans that are not withdrawable or are more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it has removed a $1.4 billion fee collection from its U.S. consumer financing, partly due to the weakness of credit card users.
However, it is too early to panic.
Losses and losses are still low.
According to the rating agency Moody's, the third-quarter drop rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in U.S. private insolvency laws in 2005 resulted in a sudden case of bankruptcy reports, which in turn accounted for a large portion of the credit card losses; the number of applications (and thus mortgage fees) would rise again whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month.
and trust in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stall in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that spending volumes for 2007 will eventually be 25% higher than last year.
