Venus is Earth's Infernal Twin
Despite its life-threatening atmosphere, Venus is more similar to the Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and winds at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in the winter.
For three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it sensed electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: the flashes on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous “original soup theory”, lightning caused life on Earth: storms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
"If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil's twin on Earth, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has undergone such a completely different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone for the Venus exploration since the early 1990s, with no spacecraft being deployed to explore the planet.
The latest research findings, now presented in several "Nature" articles, emphasize, according to the researchers, not only the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with Earth are greater than initially thought," the ESA said.
In addition to the already known north pole wind, the researchers also found a cloud-strudel on the southern pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon resembles air flows in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second deepest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also referred to as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
But it rotates much slower around itself: a Venus day takes 243 Earth days.
Although the Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained in the oceans on Earth, but on which Venus was lost into space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
