These are not Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the terms Sweden and the wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden throw dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol’s 1968 Brillo boxes a few months ago, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now come to a disturbing conclusion: The six Brillo boxes that former museum director Pontus Hultén donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies – and probably also most of the about one hundred other Brillo boxes of the “type Stockholm” in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is chained, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard of the soap powder "Brillo".
A 1968 exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet exhibited – with Warhol’s consent – hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were (for cost reasons) not from Warhol, but were supplied directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
They were not works of art, but models, merely exhibition pieces.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol granted permission to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time entered the history of art and auction as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three of the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first grounded and melted, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel with a roll of paint without grounding - in addition, it is not an oil, but acrylic paint.
“These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo boxes,” said Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet, “unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition materials.”
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the “severe accusations” raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, it has remained in implacable silence.
