United Internet becomes major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has acquired a 20% stake in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday evening.
It now holds 20.5% of the base capital.
There have been speculations about the acquisition before.
The option remains open to increasing the proportion of Versatel.
The move aims to advance the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet.
Earlier on Wednesday, assumptions about a start-up had already arisen after the Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf grid operator by another 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house holds the shares only for a third party, it said in the financial market.
Last year, United Internet owned almost 10 percent of the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth 106.4 million euros.
A total of 5.15 million shares of which United Internet bought for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started talks on marketing cooperation for DSL and mobile products.
“We are strengthening our partnership,” a United Internet spokesman explained.
The two companies have formed the joint venture MSP to take over the competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to satisfy themselves with a good ten percent stake in Freenet and do not make use of their right to acquire another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet on Thursday.
However, the two companies remained open to all options, in particular to further increase their participation in Freenet AG, it said.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The months of poker around Freenet is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and full connection customers.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch held directly 6.01 percent of Freenet shares so far.
